03972nam a22005655i 9780822395829DE-B159720201028084219.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201028t20132012ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223958297 a10.1515/97808223958292doi  a(DE-B1597)553402  a(OCoLC)1144390696  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aBF175.5.I53bM36 2013eb 7aPER0030702bisacsh04a1282231 aManning, Erin, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAlways More Than One :bIndividuation's Dance /cErin Manning. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2013] 4cÂ©2012  a1 online resource (328 p.) :b33 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPrelude -- tAcknowledgments -- t1. Toward a Leaky Sense of Self -- t2. Always More Than One -- t3. Waltzing the Limit -- t4. Propositions for the Verge -- t5. Choreography as Mobile Architecture -- t6. The Dance of Attention -- t7. An Ethics of Language in the Making -- t8. The Shape of Enthusiasm -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Always More Than One, the philosopher, visual artist, and dancer Erin Manning explores the concept of the "more than human" in the context of movement, perception, and experience. Working from Whitehead's process philosophy and Simondon's theory of individuation, she extends the concepts of movement and relation developed in her earlier work toward the notion of "choreographic thinking." Here, she uses choreographic thinking to explore a mode of perception prior to the settling of experience into established categories. Manning connects this to the concept of "autistic perception," described by autistics as the awareness of a relational field prior to the so-called neurotypical tendency to "chunk" experience into predetermined subjects and objects. Autistics explain that, rather than immediately distinguishing objects-such as chairs and tables and humans-from one another on entering a given environment, they experience the environment as gradually taking form. Manning maintains that this mode of awareness underlies all perception. What we perceive is never first a subject or an object, but an ecology. From this vantage point, she proposes that we consider an ecological politics where movement and relation take precedence over predefined categories, such as the neurotypical and the neurodiverse, or the human and the nonhuman. What would it mean to embrace an ecological politics of collective individuation?  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Okt 2020) 0aGroup identity. 0aIndividuality. 0aIndividuation (Psychology)xSocial aspects. 0aMovement (Philosophy). 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Dance / Reference.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822395829zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822395829423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822395829.jpg  a978-3-11-071183-7  DUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles